RStudio Projects

















"Organization is what you do before you do something, so that when you do it, it is not all mixed up." - A.A. Milne

Using Projects



RStudio projects make it straightforward to divide your work into multiple contexts, each with their own working directory, workspace, history, and source documents.

Let's create a project


File » New Project


So what's different?

So what's different?

When a project is opened:

  • A new R session is started
  • The .Rprofile file in the project's main directory is sourced
  • The .RData file in the project's main directory is loaded
  • The .Rhistory file in the project's main director is loaded
  • The current working directory is set to the project directory
  • Previously edited source docs are restored to the editor tab
  • Other RStudio settings (active tabs, splitter positions, etc) are restored


We can also work with multiple projects at one time

Set Project Options

There are some per-project customization options

Tools » Project Options

R Markdown

















Fully reproducible approach to turn your analyses into high quality documents, reports, presentations and dashboards.

Using R Markdown


R Markdown allows you to turn your analyses into high quality documents, reports, presentations and dashboards.

How does it work?

  1. Creating documents with R Markdown starts with an .Rmd file that contains a combination of text and R code chunks
  2. The .Rmd file is fed to knitr, which executes all of the R code chunks and…
  3. creates a new markdown (.md) document with the output
  4. pandoc then processes the .md file to create a finished…
  5. web page, PDF, Word document, slide show, etc.


Say what?


Okay, one more time, how does it work?

R Notebooks

















Interactive execution mode for R Markdown documents.

Why so Special?



1. Creates greater interactivity while creating your document

2. Easy to share your notebook directly

3. When complete, knit to the publication format desired
